AGI -&nbsp; Russian forces continue their advance > across north-eastern Ukraine, conquering a series of small settlements along the border and forcing Ukrainian troops to withdraw from some positions. This, according to both Russian and Ukrainian military sources, the situation at the front in the conflict between Moscow and Kiev. The Russians bombed the city centre. the mayor, Igor Terekhov, reported that a skyscraper was hit. Following the Russian attack at least 16 people were injured, including three children, > says RBC-Ukraine citing the head of the Kharkiv region, Oleg Synegubov and the Kiev Interior Ministry. Among the wounded - a 28-year-old man in serious condition and a 78-year-old woman in moderate conditions, who were hospitalized, and two children aged 8 and 12", added the manager of the region. Another child was hospitalized with minor injuries. In the morning the Russians had already bombed Kharkiv with two air bombs.
&nbsp;
The Ukrainian army is facing a "critical" situation in North-East of the country, due to the shortage of troops while trying to repel the Russian offensive that has progressed for several days, admitted General Kyrylo Budanov, head of the Ukrainian military intelligence agency, in a video call from a bunker in Kharkiv, according to the New York Times. "The situation is at the limit," said Budanov, "every now the situation becomes critical." Russian troops crossed the border last week to open a new line of attack near Kharkiv, the second largest city in Ukraine after Kiev, occupying at least nine settlements and villages and forcing thousands of civilians to escape.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The Russians have understood, just as many analysts, that the main disadvantage currently suffering Ukraine is men," said Franz-Stefan Gady, a military analyst living in Vienna. "Using the first line, increase the likelihood of a turn." Gady and other experts said that the immediate goal of the new Russian offensive is to force the Ukrainian army to withdraw troops south of Kharkiv, especially around the merlate city of Chasiv Yar, a Ukrainian strategic stronghold in the south-east of the region of Donetsk.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 Police chief, Vovchansk is becoming the new Bakhmut</h2>
The city of Vovchansk in the Kharkiv > region is "transforming" in Bakhmut or Maryinka > due to the continuous air attacks of the Russians.>&nbsp; The Chief Police of the Kharkiv region, Volodymyr Tymoshko, as RBC-Ukraine reports. In the three days since the beginning of the Russian offensive, Vovchansk "has suffered as it did not suffer since 2022", said Tymoshko: in particular, the Russians use a large number of air bombs guided to attack the city. "This is a 250-inch bomb or even 500 kilograms, which can demolish a multi-storey building. In a way, Vovchansk is turning into Bakhmut or Maryinka," he said. Tymoshko says the enemy's goal is not only the Ukrainian army, but also the police and rescuers. Therefore, armored vehicles are involved in the evacuation of civilians. According to the police chief of the Kharkiv region, the Russians use the tactics of the burned land, when a certain territory is bombarded with artillery and anti-aircraft guns before the entrance of the troops.&nbsp;
